   Young scientists find advantages to pursuing related problems - sometimes for years on end

   By Susan Gaidos

   Web edition: April 15, 2013
   [_]
   Enlarge
   Student Erika DeBenedictis spent years studying the so-called interplanetary superhighway, illustrated here. Her persistence paid off: In 2010, her work placed first in the premier student
   research competition for high school seniors.
   Credit: Martin Lo, Caltech

   The students (and former students) profiled here have all worked on long-term science fair projects. The tips they offer suggest how you can get started -- and the benefits from sticking with
   the same theme, digging deeper for two or more years.

